Yummy! As someone else said, this is dramatically more than the sum of its parts. I used frozen white corn, canned pinto beans, and quartered cherry tomatoes, and it was still delicious. I will definitely make again this summer when corn and tomatoes are in season. We ate this as a vegetarian main dish with soup, and it was plenty.

Rating: 3
I tried making this two different ways: 1. Beans and corn from cans vs. Fresh beans and thawed corn. Corn from a can was crisper and tastier than thawed frozen corn. 2. Basil vs. Cilatro and chile powder versions. Both were good, but really lack flavor. If you're using a very salty chip for scooping, or adding it to a dish, then the recipe is perfect. Otherwise, on it's own it is very bland and needs more salt or other spices of choice.

Rating: 4
This is one of those recipes where the end result is greater than the sum of the individual parts. Delish! Made exactly as written, but I can see how it may be adapted (with cilantro, chili powder, etc, as suggested by other reviewers) to suit different cuisines (Mexican, etc). Served with a roasted chicken and orzo w/ parmesan - a basic mid week meal. My hubby raved, the kids were ok w/ it (not big bean lovers) - and we polished the whole bowl! We were hungry, this was good, it hit the spot, and I strongly suggest you try it! You'll like it!

